We use the double angle identity for sine to rewrite the numerator. The identity is:

$$\sin 2a = 2\sin a \cos a$$

Substituting this into the expression for $P$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
P &= \frac{30(2 \sin a \cos a)}{8b} \\
P &= \frac{60 \sin a \cos a}{8b}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, we substitute $a = 45^{\circ}$ and $b = 2$ into our new expression:

$$
\begin{aligned}
P &= \frac{60 \sin 45^{\circ} \cos 45^{\circ}}{8(2)} \\
P &= \frac{60 \sin 45^{\circ} \cos 45^{\circ}}{16}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using exact values for trigonometric ratios, we know that for $45^{\circ}$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sin 45^{\circ} &= \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
\cos 45^{\circ} &= \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Multiplying these together gives:

$$\sin 45^{\circ} \cos 45^{\circ} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \times \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} = 0.5$$
